# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# .dockerignore — files EXCLUDED from Docker's build context.
#
# The build context is EVERYTHING in the directory you pass as the last
# arg to `docker build`. Anything matched here is never sent to the
# Docker daemon, which means:
#   - faster builds (less to transfer)
#   - no accidental leaks of .env/.git/editor files into images
#   - no host node_modules poisoning the container install
#
# Syntax is the same as .gitignore.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# --- Version control ---
.git
.gitignore
.gitattributes

# --- Node runtime & installs (the container makes its own) ---
node_modules
npm-debug.log*
yarn-debug.log*
yarn-error.log*

# --- Yarn 4 (Berry) caches / installer state ---
# We deliberately KEEP .yarn/releases (the pinned yarn binary) and
# .yarnrc.yml — the container's Corepack needs both to select and
# run the exact yarn version pinned in package.json.
.yarn/*
!.yarn/releases
!.yarn/patches
!.yarn/plugins
.pnp.*
.yarn/cache
.yarn/install-state.gz

# --- Build output — the container recompiles this ---
dist
build
*.tsbuildinfo

# --- Env & secrets — must NEVER enter an image ---
.env
.env.*
!.env.example

# --- IDE / editor / OS ---
.vscode
.idea
*.swp
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db

# --- Coverage / test artifacts ---
coverage
.nyc_output

# --- Docker files & compose (no need to bundle them into the image) ---
Dockerfile*
compose*.yaml
docker-compose*.yaml
.dockerignore

# --- Repo documentation — the container doesn't need our notes ---
README.md
LEARNING-APPROACH.md
stages
cheatsheets
